WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.320
So imagine you're tasked by your stakeholders to develop this dashboard to get all the information

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:11.880
that they could possibly want, right?

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:17.700
So you spend weeks gathering the data, making sure everything's there, and then you actually

00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:21.120
go to deploy it, and you think that you're going to have all this information at their

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:22.379
fingertips.

00:00:22.379 --> 00:00:26.900
And then when you actually deploy it, they actually never use it, and it ends up collecting

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:28.180
dots.

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:32.619
And so like, you know, I don't know about you, but I've experienced this multiple times.

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:37.299
And part of it is just kind of the life cycle of developing a dashboard.

00:00:37.299 --> 00:00:41.660
And I think the underlying cause is due to dashboard fatigue.

00:00:41.660 --> 00:00:45.419
Because a lot of the times the stakeholders, they say they want all these different metrics,

00:00:45.419 --> 00:00:49.580
you go and compile them, but it's just like, it's just too much data for them to handle

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:53.099
and not enough time to be able to process everything.

00:00:53.099 --> 00:00:56.500
And sometimes the key insights can get lost in the noise.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:00:58.820
Because there's so much information to look at.

00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:04.019
And then sometimes they'll have analysis paralysis, because they don't know exactly what they

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:05.019
want.

00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:08.160
Because, you know, I'm running to the next meeting, I want to know this metric rather

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:09.500
than go to the dashboard.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:14.339
I'm just going to email my data scientist to be able to give me that figure.

00:01:14.339 --> 00:01:16.980
And just a little bit of background about me.

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:21.500
I'm a data scientist at a venture capital firm based in Chicago, SVG Ventures.

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:27.260
We invest at the seams of oceans and seafood, food and agriculture, and clean energy.

00:01:27.260 --> 00:01:29.980
And I've built many, many dashboards in my time.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:34.459
And I found that, you know, sometimes you can build these dashboards, but you don't

00:01:34.459 --> 00:01:36.260
necessarily get the engagement that you want.

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:42.779
And I kind of want to share my journey of how I was able to gain additional usage from

00:01:42.779 --> 00:01:44.339
dashboards, right?

00:01:44.339 --> 00:01:48.940
And I think part of the reason is due to there's friction.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:50.620
And so friction, what I mean by that?

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:56.139
I mean that, you know, logging into like a Tableau or Power BI portal can be somewhat

00:01:56.139 --> 00:02:00.540
cumbersome for an executive that's on their phone constantly.

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:02.860
And I wanted to kind of meet them where they are.

00:02:02.860 --> 00:02:09.100
And that's typically, at least for me, in Slack or Gmail or Outlook, right?

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:14.820
And what you can do is you can kind of almost create, I want to introduce this idea of like

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:19.179
using emails to be able to deliver insights to these executives.

00:02:19.179 --> 00:02:25.539
And then you can kind of have like dynamic subjects that can kind of alert them with

00:02:25.539 --> 00:02:31.339
different KPIs or whatever metrics that you want so that they can actually act on this

00:02:31.339 --> 00:02:32.539
insight.

00:02:32.539 --> 00:02:37.339
And so the analogy that I kind of want to bring up is the idea of like the library,

00:02:37.339 --> 00:02:38.339
right?

00:02:38.339 --> 00:02:41.179
So the library has all the information that you'd want, but you kind of have to pull.

00:02:41.179 --> 00:02:44.300
You have to go in and find the information that you want.

00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:47.419
And I want to introduce the concept of like pushing the data, right?

00:02:47.419 --> 00:02:50.899
So it's almost like you have a librarian come to you and deliver that data.

00:02:50.899 --> 00:02:56.460
And then in this analogy, be using the emails to be able to dynamically deliver them to

00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:59.179
you whenever you want.

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:02.500
And you're able to do this by using a portal.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:10.100
And then you're able to identify the specific parameters that you'd want to be able to deliver

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:11.300
it to them.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:18.460
And then you can use this in both Python and R, and then you can leverage Positive Connect.

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:23.419
So just to kind of make this more of an example, I'm going to use like at a case study, so

00:03:23.419 --> 00:03:24.419
to speak.

00:03:24.419 --> 00:03:27.460
And so imagine you have a chief marketing officer, Jane.

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:31.619
She's got multiple dashboards, but then she doesn't have, she doesn't know where to search

00:03:31.619 --> 00:03:35.619
for the information that she wants because she has like seven different dashboards that

00:03:35.619 --> 00:03:38.500
she asked for, but she has limited bandwidth.

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:42.740
And so what we can do is we can identify what are the key data points that she wants at

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:44.539
whatever this particular time.

00:03:44.539 --> 00:03:48.500
And so for this example, let's say for this quarter, she's really interested in some campaign

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:52.779
why and she wants to know whenever there's new leads, right?

00:03:52.779 --> 00:03:56.699
So these are the key metric points that's going to kind of guide our principles for

00:03:56.699 --> 00:03:58.539
developing these emails.

00:03:58.539 --> 00:04:01.300
And then you'll just want to make sure you personalize the delivery.

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:05.660
So what the two things I focus on are like when, so the whenever we should send these

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:12.059
emails to them and then the so what, so like what do we want them to do it in response

00:04:12.059 --> 00:04:14.460
to said email, right?

00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:18.940
And so how I do this is I use Cordo and then the pins package.

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:25.700
And then we use Positive Connected S2G just like we saw this morning's keynote.

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:31.220
It's the platform that you can use to host all of your applications, shiny apps, and

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.179
reports easily within your enterprise.

00:04:35.179 --> 00:04:41.100
And so I use pins extensively at S2G because what I do is we have multiple data sources

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:45.540
feed into our data warehouse and in ours, we use Google Clouds, we have BigQuery.

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:51.899
But then within our Connect instance, I have a QMD file that runs every day and it's able

00:04:51.899 --> 00:04:55.140
to save model data as a pin.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:05:00.880
And then what I do is I use like I have data that's prepared for specific use cases for

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:01.880
different departments.

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.260
So in my case, like it would be marketing and finance.

00:05:04.339 --> 00:05:09.140
So I'd have marketing data that's ready to go whenever I need and then finance data and

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:10.140
so on and so forth.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:14.420
And so once you have that, there's essentially four main steps that you need to be able to

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:15.820
generate these emails.

00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:17.859
So the first one is setting up your YAML.

00:05:17.859 --> 00:05:21.980
So this is an example of a QMD report.

00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:26.660
What you need to do is all you need to do in the YAML is just change the format to email.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:28.420
And then the second one is just running your code.

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:30.140
So I'll just reference the pins.

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.299
So this one, I'll reference the marketing pin right here.

00:05:32.339 --> 00:05:37.380
And then you just run whatever R or Python code that you would normally run.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.519
And then third is just establishing your conditional email logic.

00:05:40.519 --> 00:05:45.619
So this is the brains of like delivering an email or not delivering it.

00:05:45.619 --> 00:05:51.019
And the fourth is the actual content of the email itself.

00:05:51.019 --> 00:05:57.980
So within the context of R, I use the YAML and then we use the parameters argument right

00:05:57.980 --> 00:05:58.980
here.

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:01.459
So then you can add parameters to your document.

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:07.339
So this is a way for us to modularize our documents so that you can send different variations

00:06:07.339 --> 00:06:09.079
for let's say different departments.

00:06:09.079 --> 00:06:13.820
So let's say I have a user table right here with all the individuals within my organization.

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:15.739
They belong to different departments.

00:06:15.739 --> 00:06:20.500
So you can pipe in different parameters into the document and then reference them in the

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:21.500
future.

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:22.500
Right.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:25.179
So then right here, we'll have Jane and then she's part of the marketing.

00:06:25.179 --> 00:06:28.540
You can reference this by using the params argument right there.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:35.339
And what that'll do is then render your code so that it'll just say marketing, hello, Jane

00:06:35.339 --> 00:06:39.579
and filtering on her emails right there.

00:06:39.579 --> 00:06:44.660
And so then the power of this being able to use this to be able to generate multiple documents

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:48.619
for different departments, different users, different use cases.

00:06:48.619 --> 00:06:53.500
And so J.D. Ryan had a fantastic talk last year on using purr to be able to generate

00:06:53.500 --> 00:07:00.459
multiple different documents and by using the purr package and a map family of functions.

00:07:00.459 --> 00:07:05.299
So you can kind of see here you have the I can generate a finance report or a marketing

00:07:05.299 --> 00:07:07.980
HR, what have you.

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:12.619
And so what I'm able to do is use this to generate different documents for different

00:07:12.619 --> 00:07:13.899
folks within the org.

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:16.660
And then within Python, it's relatively similar.

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:18.820
We don't use the YAML up here.

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:23.299
We just say the format is email, but then you just insert it into a Python code chunk

00:07:23.299 --> 00:07:26.339
and you have the tags parameters right there.

00:07:26.339 --> 00:07:31.660
And then you kind of pipe it similar to you do in R.

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:35.179
And then you kind of reference it by just using the curly braces Python and it works

00:07:35.179 --> 00:07:37.100
just the same.

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:39.859
The second component of the emails is just running your code.

00:07:39.859 --> 00:07:42.700
So this is running your code just as you normally would.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:45.820
Right here I'm having like an alert for the params department.

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:51.019
And then what this does is I can insert like a gplotly, like interactive graphs right here

00:07:51.019 --> 00:07:52.339
or react tables.

00:07:52.339 --> 00:07:54.579
So that has an interactivity.

00:07:54.579 --> 00:07:58.980
Whatever metrics that you normally have in your analysis, you kind of have it embedded

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:00.459
right there.

00:08:00.459 --> 00:08:04.619
And then the third component is the conditional email logic.

00:08:04.619 --> 00:08:07.220
So let's say I have neglected dashboards, right?

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:11.200
So you generated them, you want the users to be able to actually check them out.

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:16.619
So I have a shiny dashboard for my marketing team, and then I have a shiny for Python one

00:08:16.619 --> 00:08:17.959
for the finance team.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:26.119
So then you can have different QMD files that will then house your email to be able to send.

00:08:26.119 --> 00:08:28.920
And then all you need to do is define your conditional logic.

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.880
So for the marketing team, what they want to know is like whenever we have new leads,

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:35.320
just ping me in Q3.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:38.479
But then in the finance team, they want to know when we're going to be over budget, you

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:40.479
know, two weeks beforehand.

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:45.239
So then that's the logic that we're going to be using to be able to determine if we're

00:08:45.239 --> 00:08:50.440
going to send the email or not right there.

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:55.280
So then the fourth component, oops, sorry.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:09:01.080
So in terms of like making this more concrete, we can use this guiding principle of just

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.559
sending the email whenever we have leads.

00:09:03.559 --> 00:09:08.239
So what I have is I have some leads data that I have from the pin, and then you just count

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:11.599
the number of leads right there, and then you define a function.

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:14.440
So right here, I'm just doing a send email with leads.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:18.340
And then you just have the logic being that if the number of leads is greater than zero

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:23.979
and the data is in Q3, then return yes, if else, return no.

00:09:23.979 --> 00:09:27.760
So this is the actual function that we use to be able to determine if it's going to send

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:29.880
the email or not.

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:33.000
And then the fourth component is just the emails, right?

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.760
So we talked about the YAML, and then now we need to get into the specific format that

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:41.679
we embed within a Cordo doc to send the email.

00:09:41.679 --> 00:09:46.280
And so what we use is we create a .email div with the triple colons right here, and you

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:48.719
can just put plain text in here.

00:09:48.719 --> 00:09:53.200
You can insert code chunks, and then you can embed a subject.

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:56.940
So just note that you just add another div, but you do .subject.

00:09:56.940 --> 00:10:01.440
It's important to make sure that this is nested within the email.

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:07.000
And then you can kind of add dynamic things in here if you'd like as well.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.099
The third one is adding the schedule logic.

00:10:10.099 --> 00:10:13.159
So you do a .email-scheduled.

00:10:13.159 --> 00:10:18.919
And so this is where you put your conditional logic where you're actually going to evaluate

00:10:18.919 --> 00:10:20.159
whether or not to send it.

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:25.440
And so Cordo, because it supports multiple languages, the documentation says you just

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:28.760
need to return something truly or falsely.

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:33.440
So it's like yes, no, true, Python true, are true or false, right?

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:39.679
So just make sure whatever you do, you abide by that, and Cordo will take care of the rest.

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:43.880
And so this is for Cordo version 1.4 and above.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:48.799
So if you are on an older version, just make sure you at least have version 1.4.

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:54.960
And then so once you define this code right here, you say send emails with leads, and

00:10:54.960 --> 00:11:00.159
then you just evaluate it right here with the email-scheduled div.

00:11:00.159 --> 00:11:08.119
So because the number of leads is greater than zero, it's then going to send the email.

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:10.599
And then this works similarly in Python.

00:11:10.599 --> 00:11:16.840
You just define your Python code chunk, have your function, and then you basically the

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:24.580
same thing, and then you evaluate it, and it'll render based on the criteria right here.

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:30.119
And then so this is an example of how you actually implement this in the email.

00:11:30.119 --> 00:11:35.840
So notice here, I'll have the email divs, and then you have high, and then you can reference

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:36.840
the parameters.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:41.520
And then you can say, here are the number of leads that we have, and you can just reference

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:43.799
it and then insert different plots.

00:11:43.799 --> 00:11:49.119
You'll notice here that I didn't put interactive, like a ggplotly in here, because this is an

00:11:49.119 --> 00:11:50.119
email.

00:11:50.119 --> 00:11:51.119
It's like an HTML email.

00:11:51.119 --> 00:11:59.380
And then you can reference environmental variables right here, like the rs.posit.connect.report.url.

00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:01.020
So you don't have to hard code it right there.

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:02.659
You can kind of reference it.

00:12:02.659 --> 00:12:08.580
And then one tip that I have found is that whenever you're rendering like a GT, you can,

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:11.780
for the email, you just make sure you use that as raw HTML.

00:12:11.780 --> 00:12:17.539
So this preserves the formatting, or else it'll just be kind of a plain table.

00:12:17.539 --> 00:12:23.260
And so we have this as a email div, and then you can insert the subject right here.

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:27.580
The nice thing about this is that you can insert code chunks in here, like the R code

00:12:27.580 --> 00:12:28.580
chunk.

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:32.700
And so how this will render is it'll say, campaign Y is either higher or lower based

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:36.299
on the function and what it returns.

00:12:36.299 --> 00:12:40.140
And then you can actually add your conditional logic right there.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:43.299
So you'll see that, remember, everything's within the email div.

00:12:43.299 --> 00:12:45.859
You don't have to necessarily use the email scheduled.

00:12:45.859 --> 00:12:51.340
I prefer to use it, because then you can actually control when these are delivered.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:57.419
And then you can have the subject be dynamic versus just a static or hard-coded text.

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:04.700
Just to kind of put it all together, we can take this marketing QMD file, and you reference

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:05.700
the pins.

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:08.820
You have your report, your regular code that you normally have.

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:17.580
And then that will yield this QMD report that's dynamic, that has all the hover tooltips.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:21.460
And then you can sort, search, arrange, and all that stuff.

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:26.460
And then you insert your conditional email logic, and then you insert your email content.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:32.859
And what that does is then it renders a static version whenever the conditions are satisfied,

00:13:32.859 --> 00:13:33.859
if that makes sense.

00:13:33.859 --> 00:13:36.460
So then this is the dynamic version that they have it.

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:37.700
This is the static.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:39.500
And then you'll notice that it's kind of pared down.

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:43.179
It's not as full as this one, because it's just an email.

00:13:43.179 --> 00:13:48.260
But the nice thing is that you can embed URL links to, let's say, another dashboard that

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:52.260
they should be checking out based on your parameters.

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:57.419
So this is a mechanism by which you get people to actually go to the said dashboard or look

00:13:57.419 --> 00:14:01.340
at a specific report.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:09.500
In terms of delivery of these emails, what you can do is you go into your Connect console,

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:13.260
and you go to the People tab, and then you're able to create groups.

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:15.580
So in this case, I created a marketing group.

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:21.619
You can define who's actually going to be in the group, and you can add or subtract

00:14:21.619 --> 00:14:26.700
people if you'd like, or you can create individual reports for people.

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:30.979
And then you kind of provision access by saying, OK, I'm going to allow the marketing team

00:14:30.979 --> 00:14:37.140
to see this report, have this marketing URL right here, and then you can kind of schedule it.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:39.859
So this is where it renders.

00:14:39.859 --> 00:14:41.260
You can specify when it renders.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:46.500
You can have it render every hour, every day, every month, every quarter.

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:51.619
And then what will control whether they get the email or not is based on the conditional

00:14:51.619 --> 00:14:54.020
logic that you establish right here.

00:14:54.020 --> 00:15:00.299
So this would only render if we have leads that are in Q3 or not.

00:15:00.299 --> 00:15:03.739
So if you send this out, they're like, I'm getting too many emails.

00:15:03.739 --> 00:15:07.859
You can kind of tweak your logic right here.

00:15:07.859 --> 00:15:11.460
And so then the report can be up to date every single day because it's running.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:18.179
And then you change the evaluation of the parameters right there.

00:15:18.179 --> 00:15:23.059
And then some considerations with quarterly emails.

00:15:23.059 --> 00:15:26.260
Because of the nature of emails, they tend to be static.

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:28.179
So you kind of have to parse it down.

00:15:28.179 --> 00:15:32.659
You can't have super beautiful tables and large tables because it's just like it's going

00:15:32.659 --> 00:15:34.380
to be pretty small.

00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:37.619
And then you'll have limited interactivity.

00:15:37.619 --> 00:15:42.979
In terms of tips, I think the main thing that I found is just focusing on the key metrics

00:15:42.979 --> 00:15:45.340
and then using the dynamic subject lines right here.

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:49.299
So it's like you can make it so that the campaign is higher, lower, whatever.

00:15:49.299 --> 00:15:51.359
And that way it's not hard coded.

00:15:51.359 --> 00:15:54.419
And then just be selective in your delivery of criteria.

00:15:54.419 --> 00:15:58.820
That way you're not inundating people with multiple emails.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:01.900
And then always thinking about the so what.

00:16:01.900 --> 00:16:05.979
So when I deploy this at the firm, it's not like it just worked overnight.

00:16:05.979 --> 00:16:08.059
It's kind of like this continuous process.

00:16:08.059 --> 00:16:13.500
So you're just making sure you get the emails to them and then actually check are they actually

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:14.580
checking out the dashboard.

00:16:14.580 --> 00:16:20.820
So you can look at the connected admin console to kind of see are they using the dashboards

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:21.820
or not.

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:26.020
